<chapter>
	<title>Chapter 8 Questions</title>

  <exercise label="chkpt-ivp-solution">
    <title>Initial Value Problem Solution</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Which of the following is a solution to the initial value problem
        <me>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2y - 10,\quad y(0) = 8</me>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>y(x) = 3e^{2x} + 5</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct! This function satisfies the differential equation since
          <md>
            <mrow> \frac{d}{dx}\left[3e^{2x} + 5\right] \amp = 2[3e^{2x} + 5]-10 </mrow>
            <mrow>                              6e^{2x} \amp = 6e^{2x} + 10 - 10 </mrow>
            <mrow>                              6e^{2x} \amp = 6e^{2x} \quad ✅ </mrow>
          </md>
          and the initial condition, since <m>y(0) = 3(1) + 5 = 8 \quad ✅</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>y(x) = e^{2x} + 5</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          This does not satisfy the initial condition since <m>y(0) = 1 + 5 = 6 \neq 8 \quad ❌</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
        <m>y(x) = 2e^{2x} + 6</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          This satisfies the initial condition since <m>y(0) = 2(1) + 6 = 8 \quad ✅</m>, but it does not satisfy the differential equation since
          <md>
            <mrow> \frac{d}{dx}\left[2e^{2x} + 6\right] \amp = 2[2e^{x} + 6]-10 </mrow>
            <mrow>                              4e^{2x} \amp = 4e^{2x} + 12 - 10 </mrow>
            <mrow>                              4e^{2x} \amp = 4e^{2x} + 2 \quad ❌ </mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="chkpt-slope-field-matching">
    <title>Slope Field Identification</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Which slope field corresponds to each of the following first-order differential equations?
      </p>
      <p>
        Match: <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x - y</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <image source="slopefield_1.png" width="50%"/>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Compare the behavior of the slopes in this field with the equation <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x - y</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <image source="slopefield_2.png" width="50%"/>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Examine whether the slopes depend on both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> or just one variable.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <image source="slopefield_3.png" width="50%"/>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Check if the slope patterns match the expected behavior from <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x - y</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <image source="slopefield_4.png" width="50%"/>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Consider how the slopes should change as <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> vary.
        </p>
      </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <exercise label="chkpt-matching-diffeq-solutions">
    <title>Match Differential Equations with Solutions</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Match each initial-valued differential equation with its solution.
        <me/><!-- Vertical space hack. Is there a better way? -->
      </p>

			<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
				<p><m>\color{RoyalBlue}\small\text{Initial-Valued Problem}\ ⤵︎ </m></p>
				<p><m>\color{BurntOrange}\small\text{Solution}\ ⤵︎</m></p>
			</sidebyside>
    </statement>
    <feedback>
      <p>
        To verify a solution, substitute it into the differential equation and check that the initial conditions are satisfied.
      </p>
    </feedback>
    <cardsort>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = 3y,\ \ y(0) = 2</m></premise>
        <response><m>y = 2e^{3t}</m></response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise>
          <m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dt^2} = 4y,\ \ y(0) = 1,\ \ y'(0) = 0</m>
        </premise>
        <response><m>y = \dfrac{e^{2t} + e^{-2t}}{2} = \cosh(2t)</m></response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} + 2y = 0,\ \ y(0) = 5</m></premise>
        <response><m>y = 5e^{-2t}</m></response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dt^2} = -y,\ \ y(0) = 0,\ \ y'(0) = 3</m></premise>
        <response><m>y = 3\sin(t)</m></response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = -y + 2,\ \ y(0) = 3</m></premise>
        <response><m>y = 2 + e^{-t}</m></response>
      </match>
      <match>
        <premise>
          <m>
            \begin{array}{l}
              \dfrac{d^2y}{dt^2} - 2\dfrac{dy}{dt} + y = 0,\\
              y(0) = 1,\ \ y'(0) = 0
            \end{array}
          </m>
        </premise>
        <response><m>y = e^t + te^t</m></response>
      </match>
    </cardsort>
  </exercise>

